sier way of doing these sums.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did he visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, I can never remember him - he never had time to visit the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 The other children came from the same sort of homes as yourself again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 One or two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 tradesmen\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  sons were in the same class as - that I was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You mean shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Shopkeepers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did the teachers in this school single any children out for different treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 One or two - one or two had their - people - the boys that they used to - kind of fall down on now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Were there any gangs or groups in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well, we used to get - we did used to get cliques, there was - probably half a dozen of us gang up, but we never had any kind of gang wars or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you remember if there were any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, not that I can remember, we never really looked down on any of the children - any of the other children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you go on to any other school after this one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. Tha
t was the - 'til I left - they went in standards then. This - this school; started at standard three. And then went up - 'til four, five, six - and six a.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So how old would you be when you left school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I left school at thirteen. The sch
ool leaving age then had just been altered to fourteen, but there was a special proviso in the - act which said that parents of poorer - if - a parent in a - in poorer circumstances they could apply for relief. For them to leave school at thirteen. And as
 I was the oldest in the family, my mother got me off school. It was the mother who did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Would you have stayed on longer if you' had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - I don't know whether I was eager to stay on although at that time we had an examinatio
n, I think it'd take place between - when - after you were twelve, and you had a, kind of an examination to see whether you were fit to go to a secondary school. Now I passed this examination. I think my dad would have liked me to have gone. But of course
 my mother, she was - the money was the problem and at the end I never - I never went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you attend any part time education afterwards, such as evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - that was a proviso in leaving at thirteen, you had to attend evening classes
 for the - for the last year, up to the age of fourteen. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 Used to go three nights a week, a kind of a further education.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you carry on after fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. I often think that we had a better education than some of the children are getting these days. It was more precise. And more useful.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You were telling me about a little part time job you had, this was while you were at school wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When I was nine I started that job and I continued that job until I did leave school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you get the job, did someone recommended you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. The - the butcher that I worked for - the butcher that was delivering meat on a Saturday, my mother was one of his customers and - }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 strangely}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
 enough there was a kind of waiting list for - for these type of jobs in those days and - anyway - I got the job, there was me and another boy, he had two boys and then he had a youth working for him full time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What exactly did you have to do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well, I used to go at - nine o' - eight o'clock on the - Saturday morning, and the first thing I had to do was help - help him with getting the shop ready. Ther
e was the three of us, this youth who worked full time and the other boy, this part - Saturday boy along with me. Then - when the butcher had had his - breakfast - he used to start packing his orders up and we had to deliver the orders. Used to go round w
ith a basket on our arm and deliver the - probably about four or five at once, in one - in one area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So you walked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh definitely walked. Oh yes. I used to deliver - I know one house I used to go to was in Woollerton which would be matter of abou
t - I should say three mile way. I used to go there in the afternoon. I used -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How many hours did you do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I used to finish nine o'clock at night. Now in those - in those days the butchers really never started selling the meat until Saturda
y evening. And then they used to - this shop that I worked in, he had three - kind of shuttered windows on the front, glass shuttered windows, he used to take these shutters down, put a - open the shop up, put a board on the front and then he - he had a b
ig - cut all these joints up, put - fill the window full of them, and then he had a big poster he used to hang up and it used to say top price fourpence ha'penny. I can always remember that. Fourpence ha'penny a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You worked every Saturday then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Every Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 From eight in the morning 'til nine at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 'Til nine at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What about holidays, did you ever have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh goodness no. Never - never had a holiday, I mean in the school holidays I used to go there on a Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What were you paid for this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 He paid - he paid me one and six. A penny for myself and a quarter of a pound of sausage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel at that time that it was a fair wage or not for what you were doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well my mother used to think so, I mean - to mean, I used - I used to have to take me one and six home every - every Saturday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What proportion of it did you give to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I gave it her all, I used to keep the penny. I used to buy a penny packet of cocoa with a penny. And then have a mug of cocoa.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So your mother had the one and sixpence, what sort of things would it be spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well it'd go into the general family pool. Just to help out in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you get on with the other people that you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh - quite well. With the - you mean with the butcher and - oh yes, quite well, oh yes. I can't remember any - argument or anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did the butcher treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Very nice. Oh yes, he - oh yes, 
he was very - and his wife too. Oh there was no bullying or anything like that. He just told you what - take this - when you went back with - from one order - lot of orders, he'd have the other one ready for you, put it in your basket and - off you'd go, 
and of course somebody used to pay you and you used to bring the - the money back. His wife used to do the booking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You didn't have any feelings of resentment against him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. Well I thought - I thought I was lucky being able to do a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did you feel about the actual work itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I never thought - anything - only that I was doing a job, but I - I didn't resent - I didn't resent it. I didn't resent it at all. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 The only thing I wouldn't have liked to take it on - to take it on as a regular job after I left school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I do remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did doing this job on a Saturday alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. No. I used to take them all - all along - as a part of life as you might say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 That was the only part time job you had before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
That was the only part time - we did - I remember sometimes at night, now there was a - a woman against us, she used to take hairnets, women used to wear hairnets in those days, kind of a net to put their hair in, and there
 was an elastic threaded through the edges of this fine net. And we used to go at - night and especially in the winter time there used to be one or two of us lads go and we used to thread this elastic through the nets. And - I think she used to pay, but I
'
m not sure, but it's somewhere - I know we could go there and probably earn threeha'pence in the night, which you'd probably work about - three hours for that - for the threeha'pence. For threeha'pence. It's somewhere about farthing a dozen or something l
ike that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 But it was on a very casual sort of basis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Oh that was a casual - if we felt like going in, we'd go and ask her if we could come in and she used to let us come in. But it was nothing fixed really. And that money I did have for myself. I kept that money for myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well - my first full time job, I remember my mother took me out looking for a job. I was thirteen and - she got to know there was a place on Castle Boulevard opposite the castle, named Simon and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 Pickard's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
. And they used to make jacquards which was used - which were used in the lace trade. Jacquard. Yes. Jaquard. It was - it was a kind of a cardboard which was made by pasting about - according to the thickness of - required, they used
 to paste sheets of brown paper together, to form a board. Then these were put into an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 hydraulic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
 press and dried and then the edges were all trimmed and they used to punch holes in these, the same as you do with the - you know the punch operators for the -
 what is it - comptometer - computers - they'd punch holes in according to the pattern of the lace and these run on the lace machines to work the pattern you see. This firm were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 jacquard}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  card makers. Or board makers, not card. I think it was jaquard board makers, that's what they call it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Your mother helped you to get this job you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Me mother took me to this job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did you actually have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - I worked - with a man on what was called a pasting machine, pasting these paper
s. Pasting these sheets of paper. I was at the one end of the machine, which was a big wooden tank - and in this big wooden tank - were two rollers. One of these rollers ran in the paste.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you tell me what you were doing in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I w
orked on what was called a paste machine. I worked with a man. I was at one end of the machine and the man was at the other. Both of us had sheets of brown paper. Now - this machine was like a big square cask, wooden cask, which was filled with paste, I s
h
ould say a matter of about three foot high, the cask, and inside the cask ran a big roller with another one on the top to shape - just like a big mangle. And through these rollers strings ran, under the rollers underneath, a continuous belt of strings, tw
i
ne, we used to put them on and take them off at the end of the week. And I fed a sheet of paper onto these strings through the rollers. This sheet was pasted on both sides, the man at the other end, he had these sheets of paper, he put one on a table, the
 pasted sheet on the top of it and then another dry sheet on the top of that. And he could go on 'til we got either - a thickness of seven sheets, nine sheets, eleven sheets, just the thickness that was required for these -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What was he called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I should say he would be known - not a skilled operation at all I don't think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What hours did you work here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I worked from eight o'clock in the morning 'til six at night with an hour for dinner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you ever work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Not a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Saturday morning from eight - eight 'til twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No holidays with pay. We had a weeks holiday at August, I know I wasn't there long enough to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Five shilling a week. Five shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel at that time that that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well - a boy, it was a usual starting wage for a boy that was going into any - pretty much the same, some used - some were used - some used to pay a little bit more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you give any of this money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I gave it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well again it went into the - just the keep for the whole family. Into the house-hold fund.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you get on with the other people that you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh quite all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you know your employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
No, I never saw him. Never saw him. There was a - it wasn't a big place, there was a manager there. I suppose there'd only be about a dozen people work in the place. I never saw the man who -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So you didn't have any feelings about him, or did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, I couldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did you think about the job itself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - the job itself, I - I didn't like it, there was not enough, it just seemed to be to m
e like being chained to a - a wheel and - another thing about it - at the weekend, on the Saturday morning when we'd done on the Saturday morning, we had to clean the machine down and I was the one who had to get into this paste stuff and - when I got hom
e I used to stink to all eternity. And my mother always used to be on about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You got this job in 1910, when you were thirteen, fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, 1909 I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have any other jobs before you went in the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes. Oh I left that 
job in 19 - I left that job in - I only worked there from - when I left school up 'til - I should say it'd be after the August holiday. Or the end of August, that was when I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Then where did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - my mother - lady next door to us, t
he neighbour next door to us, one of the girls worked at Players and - she spoke for me at Players. Players the cigarette people, and - I went there, I remember I went there on the Friday. And we saw the foreman there and I should have started on the Mond
a
y at Players but during the weekend some of the lads that I played with they worked at the Raleigh - Raleigh Cycle Company. And one of them told me that they wanted a lad in the repair shop at the Raleigh. This was on the Friday night. So on the Saturday 
m
orning I went myself to the Raleigh, and I asked for this - repair shop foreman, they were the people who used to do all the setting on in those days, I asked for the repair shop foreman, he said - the first thing he said to me, he says, can you ride a bi
ke? I said, yes, and I couldn't. But anyway I got the job and that was seven and six a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did you have to do in this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - my job there, I was in the repair shop I was what was called the shop lad. Now - my first job, I went - I wen
t to work - started work at half past seven. Now, the man - all work started at six o'clock, they used to work from six in the morning 'til six at night. And my first job was to collect their mashings, their tea mashings - if they'd got anything for their
 
breakfast like an egg to boil or a bit of bacon to cook or anything like that - and I used to take it to the Canteen in readiness for them coming out for their breakfast at half past eight. And then my jobs in the shop were - ordinary shop lad, running - 
running errands and sweeping the shop and - going down for the - firms depot, the Raleigh depot in King Street, probably talking a machine down and fetching another one back that wanted overhauling and all that business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You mentioned hours of work, what about Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well we used to work - we used to work then in those days, I worked from half past seven 'til six o'clock, five days a week. Half past seven - I think it was half past twelve on the Saturday. And the men worked from six o'clock in
 the morning 'til six at night, with half an hour for breakfast. They had half an hour for breakfast and an hour for dinner, but I didn't - of course I didn't have the half hour for breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have any holidays with pay then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, there was no holidays with pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 And you were paid seven and six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I thought at the time - as my other job was five shilling a week I thought it was - was big increase.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you give this money to your mother also?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes. My mother used to give me - for spending money she used to give me a penny in the shilling. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 The money you gave your mother went into the family pool?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes, it all went into the general fund, which my mother used to handle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you get on with the people there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh very nice, they were all a nice set of chaps, who I worked - I was the only boy among all men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You wouldn't know your employer at Raleigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, no. I think all the while I worked at the Raleigh I didn't see him above half a dozen times - and I worked there all me life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel anything at all about him as an employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh - I used to think he was the - he was the big noise, he was the boss, he'd got no spec
ial liking for him at all. No sense of loyalty I don't think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you feel about your actual job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I liked it very much. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You had another job with Raleigh then didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you tell me about that one then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well, it was in the wheel department. Yes. Where they used to make the cycle wheels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What sort of job did you have to do in the wheel department?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - they made the cycle wheels there and - boys and girls - boys up to the age of about fifteen, 
from thirteen to fifteen, used to lace the wheels. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 That\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
 put the spokes in the wheels. Yes. And then they were - then these wheels were tightened up and then - there were men, which were a skilled operation, on trueing. Wheel trueing - trueing the wheel. 
When boys were - after the boys were fifteen they were generally put to work with these men, helping the men, the men used to pay them and - their job was too really tighten the wheels and what we used to call rough true them. And then the men used to fin
ish them off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So how long did you work in the wheel department then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - I worked in the wheel department 'til the outbreak of war. In 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Then what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Then of course I went in the - Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Until 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Came out in 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What jobs have you done since the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - when I came back - when I came back out of the - when I came back out of the Army I - went back into the wheel shop. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You went into the wheel trueing department?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I went into the - went back into the department as a wheel truer, a job which I'd been doing when - when I joined the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 forces}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did you do then, you stayed at Raleigh all your working life?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You went into the wheel trueing department in 1919, you didn't stay in there all your working life though did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
No. After I'd been - after we'd been back there was - quite a few - well - I should say about half a dozen of us that had been in the forces that had left the shop that had lef
t the shop to go in the forces, and - in the first world war, when the war was finished a man couldn't be released out of the forces unless he'd got a job to come back to. And the firm had to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 The firm applied for your release when they'd got a place for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So you came back in 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
I came back in - about April 1919. They applied for my release and - I went back onto the same job that I was doing. But I wasn't back there long before I - I understood that - I was really a man do
ing a - a juvenile or a youth's job. And - after being back for a month or two - along with a lot of - a lot more men who had been transferred - who had come out of the forces, we were transferred onto a - into a department where they'd got a night shift.
 
And we were all put on nights. And - we were doing on nights the same jobs that women and children - juveniles were doing during the day. And this job lasted - we went - I think I went in there somewhere about June and - in October one night we went in an
d
 - the foreman told us not to take our coats off. And when we were all in, he said, well, he says, I've got some bad news for you, you've all been suspended. They knocked this - they knocked the shop off - the job off. All the night work. So - we had to s
i
gn on. On the dole. But the funny thing - the peculiar thing was that - we weren't sacked, we were suspended. All the - the - employers at that time were supposed to employ - so many returned men. And - the firm daren't sack us, but they suspended us and 
-
 as I say the difference was between being sacked and suspended, we didn't get any dole. I got no dole money, I'd drawn I think it was twenty-eight pound gratuity when I left the forces and all this money went on - on - keeping myself during the time, I w
as single of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 As things got a bit better you moved into another department?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well - we had a - we had a - deputation meet the management and - about this matter of being suspended and that and - the manager, he didn't know anything at all a
bout it, or he said he didn't, but he arranged for us to have our cards. There was a test case made, they used to have these tribunals to test cases, and - we won the case and we drew all the back money, which I think then was about twenty-nine shilling a
 week, the - unemployment pay. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When things picked up you went back to Raleigh did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
I went back to Raleigh, they - I went - actually there had been a - a kind of a re-organisation in the department that I'd left and - there was - they'd upgraded - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 upgraded}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  the prices because they couldn't get - because they wouldn't get the people to do the job and we were put back on the same job, wheel trueing, and we got - instate reinstated as - as adult labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How long did you go on with this then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well - I did that job - we used to - in those days the - used to do - oh a tremendous amount of short time. The cycle trade was a seasonable trade. We used to start work about - we'll say somewhere about - January preparing for - for the summert
ime, and then at the end of the summer we'd finish. Well - before the end of the summer because we'd done all the work for - to carry the - the trade over the summer period. And - often -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You were at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 Raleigh\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  all your working life then weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Bar - with the exception of one period when I was away for somewhere about eighteen month I think it was, when the things were very bad and I went somewhere else, but then I went back again. And I went back then into another department altogether, I w
ent into the enamelling department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
About 1930, something like that. And I stayed in the - the enamelling department until - I retired in 1962, and I was the - I was foreman then, in the department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you serve an apprenticeship or training period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 None at all. None - never had any special training at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you belong to any trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I belonged to a trade union from - coming out of the forces - in the - after the war. It's be a matter of about - I sho
uld say somewhere about two or three years after. I know we were in a trade union at the time of the general strike, 1926.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What union was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I think it was the - Municipal and General Workers, something like that, either that or the Transport a
nd General Workers, it was a - not really a skilled occupation. It was skilled but - there was not a lot of people in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you take part in any of the trade union activities?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, not that I - I was - one period, in the wheel shop I was the shop steward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel that the employers and the workers had the same interests or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I think they were totally opposed. All - in those days at least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest amongst the workers, 
for instance some people said that there was a division between the craftsmen and the general labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well, there was always - there did seem to be about a difference - a difference in that. I mean, a craftsman, he did - he belonged to his own part
icular union. I mean the firm where I worked, I should suppose there would be at least about twenty different unions there. Sheet - there was the sheet metal workers, millwrights, A.E.U., all - all different unions, brass finishers, metal polishers, all d
ifferent kinds of unions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So you would say this division was reflected in the different trade unions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
In the different - I should say there was a certain - I wouldn't say stand-offishness but - the men who were in really the skilled trades - they
 thought - and they were - no doubt about it - they were the elite. They were the elite. For instance, I mean the job that I was doing at the Raleigh, it was a skilled job at the Raleigh but when I came out of the gates of the Raleigh I - I - realized tha
t I'd got no skill at all to take anywhere else. Where a millwright or something like that could simply go anywhere. Same as a fitter. My skill -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Was specifically - for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 Raleigh\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Would you say that full time work changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Oh - after the second world war, yes. Definitely. I mean, the first thing that we knew after the second world war was - the - hours was - was reduced. From - for - without any - trouble at all, they went down from forty-seven to forty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Yes. I lived with mother - mother and father. After I'd left school for - I should say I should be fourteen, it wouldn't be long after I left school, my mother died. And - we con
tinued to live - with my father. Me father had one or two - he had two different - with trying - you know, housekeepers, but he - couldn't - he couldn't either they couldn't stand us or we couldn't stand them and - anyway we - the time of his death we wer
e all kind of together, we - mucking in together. My sister and myself and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So you went into digs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I went into lodgings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When me father died. The family broke up. My brothers and sister went to - live at Melton
 Mowbray where my mother's people were living at that time, and I went into lodgings with some people that lived about three doors away from me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 
They - they told me when I - when my dad died, they said, well we don't want you but we're not going to see you without a home, and they were very, very good to me.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Your younger brothers and sister went off to relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 They went to Melton Mowbray to live - my sister went to me grandmother's, one of me brothers went to one aunt and another brother to an
other aunt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you spend Sunday any different to any other days of the week, did you go to church or Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. Not when I'd left school. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, none - none at all. None at all. I mean, we didn't have a vote or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When were you married, what year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I was married in 1920. Christmas 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I didn't take any interest in politics until I came out of the forces.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What were your views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well - when I came out of the forces my views were Conservative. The - the person who changed my politics was the man I - who I lived with, he started - he - who I lodged with, he started - talking to me about the - the ways of th
e - the world and all this that and the other and I changed my politics. And I've never changed the since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Why do you think that you had Conservative views at the beginning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Now that I can't say. That I can't say, other than the fact that my fa
ther was a Conservative. I'd had no reason during the war to change my mind, we never discussed - I can't remember discussing politics while I was in the forces. When I came out. And another thing which really did consolidate it was the - was the general 
strike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
You were telling me about how you spent your spare time when you were at school, did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way when you started work or did you do things differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - it was slightly - slightly different
 I should say. We used to - go down to the football match, we could get in a football match for threepence then. And - used to go into town, go to the Hippodrome and tuppence in the gallery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You went out in the evening then did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - not in the week, just on a Saturday night, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 And it would be to places like the Hippodrome?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Like the Hippodrome, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Who would you go with at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - boys of my - the same age as myself, there was - one or two about 
- one or two of the same - one or two the same age round the - in the area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you make any new friends, boys or girls, round about this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well not girls. No, I can't remember having any interest in girls at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 But you were making new friends amongst boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Among boys we did -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How did you meet them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well when we were at work, you left - you see you learn some friends at school and then when you start work you get other friends. Well I don't know about friends really acquaintances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 At that time did you bring friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
No. You might a boy - a boy you were playing with might have popped in and mother might give him a drink of ginger beer or something like that. I'd go into another boy's home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
No other than about three or four boys used to pal up together or go down to the football match together and go out together on a Saturday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did our parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well I can't - I can't remember there was any affinity between my father and my friend at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did your father expect to know where you were going if you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - he - he liked us to be in at a certain time. But - he didn't put any - real ban on it, o
r - he never used to say, where are you going, or - I used to tell, just tell him where I was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 When you got married how old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I was twenty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How long had you known your wife then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 About - well I met my wife in 1919 - about - March, 1919. And we were married in December 1920, so nearly two years I should say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you remember how you met?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 We both met at work. She worked in the same department that I worked in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 She came - originally - well, she lived in Nottingham, but originally she came from Alfreton. In Derbyshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you save up before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well we never had any chance to save up. We - what we used to do, the only thing we could do, we - for a - f
or the wedding, we used to buy a bit of - so much each week perhaps a tin of that and a tin of this and - but we never really had funds, any funds to get married with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Could you describe the wedding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well we had a nice wedding, we - we - as a m
atter of fact we were only talking about it - it was our golden wedding Christmas, and - we were talking about it then, we had quite a few of the people who were at the wedding at the golden wedding. The - the best man, the bridesmaid - one of my pals who
 
played the piano, another one who sang. They were all there. And - it was quite nice to see so many people there at were at the wedding. What we did - I remember we took a - ever a workshop on the opposite right side of the way to where my wife lived, a m
a
n used to make wicker baskets and things like that, and we asked him if we could use his - workroom. - He said, with pleasure. My wife and her sisters went over and cleaned the place through and decorated it up a bit. We carted the piano across from - the
 
wife's piano. - Or the - the wife's mother's piano, and we had a really good night. But - one of the - the strange - not the strange thing but the usual thing at the time - the day after we were married, the wife and I both went down to the Labour Exchang
e to sign on. We were out of work. And we were out - I was out of work for three month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Was it customary to have wedding presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No - we had - oh certain we had presents, not - not the expensive presents which they buy - I mean I suppose one of
 my presents for the golden wedding - would have bought all the lot for the wedding - the original wedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. My wife never had any - my wife never even had an engagement ring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Where did you live after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Well we lived with the wife's mother. For - about two years. I'm - not quite two years. And then - we got a house - a friend of mine who I worked with at the Raleigh who - an old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 school friend
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 , he told me about a house becoming empty next door to him, and we got this house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How old was your wife when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did your wife have a job when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well, she - she had this job - and she kept this job on for - I should say a matter of about - two y
ear - two year - two to three year. And then she had a - illness, she was - not quite up to it so she knocked off work. That's after we'd been married about two year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What sort of jobs has she had since then or hasn't she had any since then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 We
ll, no, the only time - my wife has never had a full time job since then, she's had enough to do in the house. The only job that she did she did a part time job during the war, the latter end of the war I had rheumatic fever - during this is the second wo
rld war, and I had a long spell - and - the wife went out to work part time. When I - I was beginning to pull round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How many children did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What were their dates of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 They weren't born before 1918 were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you tell me a bit about Radford in Nottingham, about how far it is from the town }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - Radford - was a - really a community of its own, more like an industrial village. There was a railway stati
on there, Radford, and I should say it was - it was on the western outskirts of Nottingham. A matter of about three miles from the town }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You were telling me you went out to live with some other people until you were about eight or nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes. My - my mother was out of - out to work, she was a - a silk winder at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 
Hollin\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  who were afterwards purchased by Vyella. And - she put me out to nurse with some people who lived further away from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  of Nottingham, a place called Radford Woodhouse, which was - about - I should say threequarters of a mile from Radford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You lived-in there didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
Yes. I lived with the people there, there - their name was Harrison and they - there was the mother and father, two sons and a daughter. And
 one of the time - the time that I lived there one of the sons was away, he was in the Grenadier Guards; a full - a regular soldier, and he was fighting in the Boer War. I distinctly remember him coming back after the war with - the whole place was decora
ted up with welcome home and all this, that and the other. Afterwards he went down the pit, the father and two sons were - were all miners, all the three of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What was the name of the street in Radford Woodhouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Vane Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What's the area called now then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
It's still called Radford Woodhouse and the streets are still there, there were three streets. That was one, Chapel, no public house or beerhof. And - it was - further - from the - when you went away from Radford from going from the city }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340  you was right in the open country, it was right on the edge of Nottingham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 How old were you when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - now I can't remember when I went there, my first recollection is of being there. I should imagine that I sho
uld be about two years old, probably younger when I was put there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You lived there and you used to go back to your mother and father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I lived there with these people, occasionally my mother used to come to see me and - I used to visit my mother
 and father just the same as - an ordinary child would visit - relatives, live at home and visit relatives. And I never lost touch with me mother and father. But when I - when I went home whenever I could get back to these people I used to get back there,
 on a Saturday or a Sunday and - the sons were very fond - used to carry - I've recollection now of one of the sons carrying me on his shoulders, sitting astride his shoulders up into the woods and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 They treated you just like one of their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 They treated me just like one of their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You were telling me Mrs Fellows had a job before you were married, can you tell me a bit about the job that she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 My wife? Well - Mrs Fellows, my wife, I met - I met her at the - working at the R
aleigh cycle company and she worked in the same department as me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did she actually do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
She was wheel builder, lacing cycle wheels. And then afterwards she went onto - cycle rims, punching the holes in cycle rims, on an automatic punch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 She didn't work after she was married to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
She worked - she worked for about - I should say - when we - when we got married we went - we lived with her - with her mother, she had no father, father was killed in the pit and she was thirteen. But w
e lived with her mother - and the family, and then for about two years, and then we got a house of our own, and she went to work then for about twelve month, probably a little longer. She was none too well, so we decided it was time for her to knock off w
ork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 You were telling me she did take a job during the second world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
During the second world war I had rheumatic fever and - I was ill for about nine month. I started back to work but I only worked about a fortnight and I had a relapse. I cam
e home from work, I had to - I'd visit the hospital gain, and my wife - we'd had nine month, we was right down to rock bottom and my wife decided it was time she did something about it and she got a part time job at Players. At John Players, the tobacco -
 cigarette people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What did she do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 I think she was on a packing machine, working in a team on an automatic packing machine packing the cigarettes in packets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Your sister, Doris, she didn't marry did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No. My sister Doris nev
er married, she - my - I've mentioned before that my mother and father died when I were - when we was very young, my - my sister would be - thirteen when my father died, he died after me mother. And the family was broken up. I stayed, I've mentioned this 
b
efore I think, that I stayed with - I went to lodge with some people who lived next door but one to us and carried on my work at the Raleigh. Well the other members of the family, my two brothers and my sister went to me mother's people who were then livi
n
g at Melton Mowbray. And my sister - when she left school I think she was on the verge of leaving school, I'm not sure, but she went out to work with the district nurse. And - she's now seventy - seventy - one in September and she's been in domestic servi
ce all her life. She never married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Your brother went to Belfast and had a rough time of it, you said he was destitute for some time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Can you tell me just a bit more about that, when he went there, why he became destitute and when he came back to this country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - I - I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
How about your brother Frank, he was the one that went in the Army wasn't he, can you tell me a bit more about him, he went in the Army and then afterwards he went to Belfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Well - he - when he came back - when he - he lived with one of my aunts in Melton }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8282280\charrsid815340 Mowbray}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
 after - after my father died the family broke up, he lived with this aunt and - it would be about 1921 this aunt wrote to me and asked me if I'd got over and see her. She was expectin
g another baby and she hadn't got room for him. So I brought him to us, we were at that time living with the wife's mother. And his - the wife's mother said, well bring him to us, we'll have to find a home for him somehow you see. And he came to live with
 us. And - when he'd been with us for some time he worked as a hosiery trimmer at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 Horley's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
. He fell out of work and - I had a talk to him and I told him, well it was rather a peculiar position and I - I advised him as the best thing for his own security was
 to join the Army. And he joined the Durham Light Infantry. He went for seven years in - in with the colours and five years on reserve. We expected - but when he'd done his seven years that he'd come back and live with us. We'd all - by that time the wife
 
and I had got a house. And we expected that he would be coming back to us. But the first - thing we heard after we knew he'd done his time - was a letter from him in Belfast and he sent us a photograph of a girl, and obviously during his war service - dur
i
ng his Army service he'd served in Ireland, In Northern Ireland, at Newtownards. Newtownards. And - during this time he'd got - made the acquaintance of a girl. And he wrote and told us that he was going to get married and he sent us a photograph of this 
g
irl. Well - we never heard much more about him, we did have an occasional letter and then - I had a letter from him to say that he'd got married but apparently this girl that he'd gone back to Belfast to find - she'd gone to Australia. I don't - whether s
h
e was married or not I don't know, but he'd got the acquaintance of another girl at that time and we didn't hear any more for a month or two and then I had a letter from which was - well he - he mentioned about committing suicide, he was right down and ou
t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 This would be about 1933 time would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
This would be about 1934 probably, he'd probably been in Ireland a year. Well I got this letter, I took this letter - to a friend that I - that I knew was a man - interested - very interested in the Bri
tish Legion, as a matter of fact he was on the welfare committee of the British Legion. I wasn't a member of the British legion but I showed him this letter and he said, let me have this letter and I'll show it our secretary. And he took it down to the he
a
dquarters and showed it the secretary, and apparently the Nottingham branch of the British Legion wrote to the secretary of the Belfast branch and asked for a report and - he told me, they showed me this report they'd got back. My brother had come to the 
p
osition where he was practically going round from door to door selling bootlaces and things like that. But - anyway I think it was through the offices of the British Legion in Belfast that they found him a little job, they found him a job as a clerk to - 
a
n auctioneer, auctioneering valuer. And he used to go round the auctions and - tabulate all the stuff, - make an inventory of all the stuff to be sold and did all the booking and that with this auctioneer. But he - he'd got a very small - very small wage.
 
I think as a matter of fact, I don't think his money was more than about twenty-five shilling a week. I think in those days, you see, he was a Protestant, and he had a terrible - and he was courting at the time, afterwards I found out he was courting a Ca
tholic girl. And he afterwards changed his religion. But he told us he was in Belfast during the times of the troubles and he used to tell us all the - stark things that happened during this - time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 He eventually came back here didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 He came
 - he came over, he came over to see us, he and his wife came on holiday. And it was just prior to the war. To the last war. Yes. And he told me then that he - of his difficulties, they'd got a house, his wife, she was a - as a matter of fact she worked i
n
 a - according to what I understood - in a factory where they made leather goods, like - handbags and all that kind, she was a seamstress, a machine operator. He was doing this job, but he told me about the money that he was getting and he was anxious to 
g
et back to England. And so was his wife. Anyway it was - this would be about - just before the war broke out in 1939 when he was on holiday and - as a matter of fact I think he came to us about October, the was started in September and he came to - 1939 -
 
and he came to us in October. I knew the war was - just started really. I got him a job - at the Raleigh, and some friends that we knew - that the wife knew, got his wife a job in the making up trade, in the - as a machinist in the making up trade in Nott
ingham. Clothing, making clothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 What was his job at Raleigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 He was a store - on - worked in the store - a storeman, storeman.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So he was much better off now then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Oh he - he'd got a reasonable job, his wife had got a reasonable job
. They put in - they lived with us, with the wife and I and the family. They put in for a council house and - there was quite a lot of council houses knocking about at the time with - young people going into the forces, young men going into the forces and
 the wives giving up the houses and going back to their parents - going to live with their parent and - they very soon got - a council house, on the Bestwood Estate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Did he keep that job until he died then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 He - he kept that job until he died. An
d he died - he was none too good when he came to us, but there was a remarkable improvement when he got - he told us how they'd lived with food, how they'd had to scrap along and - I know he - he did, he really picked up while they lived with us, the wife
 
fed him, she did, she fed him up and - but anyway when he went to live with his - he and his wife left us they were both working and - I think he neglected - either she neglected him or he neglected himself and he - he had T.B. He had T.B. And when he - w
hen he'd been ill for some time they sent him in the - Bagthorpe sanatorium, which is the city hospital in Nottingham now. And it was - he was in the sanatorium of course in those days }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11889103\charrsid815340 
Tuberculosis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 , it was only fresh air and - rest that they had - the only thing that they could prescribe for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 So he died 1942 then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
He came - he was in the hospital and - he was there about three month. And - I went to see him one day and the male nurse who was in-charge of the ward, he called me into his office a
nd asked me if I'd have a word with my brother. I said, why, what's the matter? He said, well - he'd got it on his - on his mind that he wants to go out. He said, we want him to stop in for at least another three month, he's coming on ever so well. But - 
a
nyway I went and - had a talk to him, but I could seen when I - I was usually able to convince him or to - help him anyway, he always looked upon me as big brother, but - I found out that I was - bashing me head up against a wall because he wouldn't be - 
a
nd anyway, when I was going out of the ward I asked the - the make nurse asked me about him and I said, well, I said, I'm afraid I've had no luck, I said, he's determined to come out. And afterwards we found out, he didn't say anything at the time, but af
t
erwards we found out that - it was his wife that - was causing him the trouble. She was living on her own and - he came out, I remember the words of this - male nurse. He says to me, he says, oh, he says, it's a pity. He says, they walk out, he said, but 
we always carry 'em back. And he said - that did actually happen with him, he was carried back and when he went back he died inside a month.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14102193 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 He didn't have a very happy life altogether then did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 No, he - he had the - he had the worst break of any of us. He had a real rough break. And he was a real nice lad. Have we done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7889384 HF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 Yes.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid14102193 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15428707\charrsid815340 
\par }}